# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chan-zuckerberg-initiative
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The proposition decreased property taxes by assessing values at their 1976 value, limiting the rate of taxation to 1% of the assessed value, and restricting annual increases of assessed value to an inflation factor, not to exceed 2% per year.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It prohibits reassessment of a new base year value except in cases of (a) change in ownership, or (b) completion of new construction.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] These rules apply equally to all real estate, residential and commercial—whether owned by individuals or corporations.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Significantly, the initiative also requires a two-thirds majority in both legislative houses for future increases of any state tax rates or amounts of revenue collected, including income tax rates.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It also requires a two-thirds majority in local elections for local governments wishing to increase special taxes.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 has been described as California's most famous and influential ballot measure; it received enormous publicity throughout the United States.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Passage of the initiative presaged a "taxpayer revolt" throughout the country that is sometimes thought to have contributed to the election of Ronald Reagan to the presidency during 1980.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Of 30 anti-tax ballot measures that year, 13 passed.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The proposition has been called the "third rail" (meaning "untouchable subject") of California politics, and it has generally been unpopular for lawmakers to attempt to change it.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] As a consequence of Proposition 13, homeowners in California receive a property subsidy that increases the longer that they own their home.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 declared property taxes were to be assessed their 1976 value and restricted annual increases of the tax to an inflation factor, not to exceed 2% per year.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] A reassessment of the property tax can be made only when a) the property ownership changes or b) there is construction done.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The state has been given the responsibility of distributing the property tax revenues to local agencies.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 also requires two-thirds (2/3) voter approval for cities, counties, and special districts to impose special taxes.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] 3d 585 (June 1987), the California Court of Appeal for the Second District determined that the two-thirds (2/3) voter approval requirement for special taxes under Proposition 13 applied to citizens initiatives.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] There are several theories of the origins of Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The evidence for or against these accounts varies.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Due to severe inflation during the 1970s, reassessments of residential property increased property taxes so much that some retired people could no longer afford to remain in homes they had purchased long before.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] A 2006 study published in *Law & Society Review* supported this explanation, reporting that older voters, homeowners, and voters expecting a tax increase were more likely to vote for Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 is not the only law in California designed to prevent tax-induced displacement.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The California Tax Postponement Program, passed in 1977, ensures that "homeowners who are seniors, are blind, or have a disability to defer current-year property taxes on their principal residence if they meet certain criteria".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Another explanation is Proposition 13 drew its impetus from the 1971 and 1976 California Supreme Court rulings in *Serrano v.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Priest*, which somewhat equalized California school funding by redistributing local property taxes from wealthy to poor school districts.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] According to this explanation, property owners in affluent districts perceived that the taxes they paid were no longer benefiting their local schools, and chose to cap their taxes.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] A problem with this explanation is that the *Serrano* decision and school finance equalization were popular among California voters.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The study said the tax revolt was not limited to white voters nor associated with rising conservatism associated with the collapse of the "New Deal order" and the election of Ronald Reagan.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Another explanation that has been offered is that spending by California's government had increased dramatically during the years prior to 1978, and voters sought to limit further growth.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The evidence supporting this explanation is limited, as there have been no studies relating Californians' views on the size and role of government to their views on Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It is true that California's government had grown.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Between 1973 and 1977, California state and local government expenditures per $1,000 of personal income were 8.2% higher than the national norm.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] From 1949 to 1979, public sector employment in California outstripped employment growth in the private sector.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] By 1978, 14.7% of California's civilian work force were state and local government employees, almost double the proportion of the early 1950s.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] One example of the massive expansion of government in California in the decades before Proposition 13 was the rapid growth of public postsecondary education and its expansion into almost every urban area in the state.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 1900, California had only a single public university at Berkeley, the University of California, and state normal schools which provided two-year teacher training programs at Chico, Los Angeles, San Diego, and San Francisco.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 1907, the American junior college movement was launched in California when the state legislature authorized high schools to offer lower-division college-level coursework, thereby enabling more high school graduates to attempt such courses without having to move away for college.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] California was the proud leader of this movement, in that the United States went from zero junior colleges in 1900 to nineteen by 1915, of which eight were based in California.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 1960, the Master Plan for Higher Education provided that junior colleges would be established within commuting distance of nearly all California residents, which required the founding of twenty-two new colleges on top of the sixty-four colleges already operating as of 1960.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 1967, the junior colleges were renamed "community colleges" and became part of the California Community Colleges system.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Before Proposition 13, community college districts were able "to levy certain taxes for special purposes without a vote of the public".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Among these purposes were community services, fringe benefits, and child care.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] For example, before 1978, the North Orange County Community College District levied a special tax on all property owners in the district which funded a comprehensive health care plan generous enough to amount to an overall 4% increase in compensation for all employees.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] By severely curtailing the ability of community college districts to levy property taxes, Proposition 13 shifted the state's contribution to community colleges from 38% to 78% of their revenue.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] During the early 1960s, there were several scandals in California involving county assessors.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] These assessors were found rewarding friends and allies with artificially low assessments, with tax bills to match.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] These scandals led to the passage of Assembly Bill 80 (AB 80) in 1966, which imposed standards to hold assessments to market value.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The return to market value in the wake of AB 80 could easily represent a mid-double-digit percentage increase in assessment for many homeowners.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] As a result, a large number of California homeowners experienced an immediate and drastic rise in valuation, simultaneous with rising tax rates on that assessed value, only to be told that the taxed monies would be redistributed to distant communities.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Cynicism about the favoritism of the tax system towards the wealthy and well-connected persisted into the 1970s.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The ensuing anger started to form into a backlash against property taxes which coalesced around Howard Jarvis, a former newspaperman and appliance manufacturer, turned taxpayer activist in retirement.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Howard Jarvis and Paul Gann were the most vocal and visible advocates of Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 passed with roughly two-thirds of those who voted in favor and with the participation of around two-thirds of registered voters.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] After passage, it became article XIII A of the California Constitution.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Under Proposition 13, the annual real estate tax on a parcel of property is limited to 1% of its assessed value.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] This "assessed value" may be increased only by a maximum of 2% per year until, and unless, the property has a change of ownership.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] At the time of the change in ownership the low assessed value may be reassessed to complete current market value that will produce a new base year value for the property, but future assessments are likewise restricted to the 2% annual maximum increase of the new base year value.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The property may be reassessed under certain conditions other than a change of ownership, such as when additions or new construction occur.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The assessed value is also subject to reduction if the market value of the property declines below its assessed value, such as during a real estate slump.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Reductions of property valuation were not provided for by Proposition 13 itself, but were made possible by the passage of Proposition 8 (Senate Constitutional Amendment No.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] 67) during 1978 that amended Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Such a real estate slump and downward reassessments occurred during 2009 when the California State Board of Equalization announced an estimated reduction of property tax base year values due to negative inflation.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The property tax in California is an ad valorem tax meaning that the tax assessed generally increases and decreases with the value of the property.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In the year after Proposition 13 was passed, property tax revenue to local governments declined by roughly 60% statewide.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] However, by 2003, the inflation-adjusted property tax collected by local governments exceeded the pre-1978 levels, and has continued to increase.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 2009, the advocacy group Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association estimated that Proposition 13 had reduced taxes paid by California taxpayers by an aggregate $528 billion.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Other estimates show that Proposition 13 may not have reduced California's overall per-capita tax burden or State spending.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The think tank Tax Foundation reported that in 1978, Californians had the third highest tax burden as a proportion of state income (tax-per-capita divided by income-per-capita) of 12.4% ($3,300 tax per capita, inflation adjusted).
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] By 2012, it had fallen slightly to the sixth highest rate, 10.9%, ($4,100 tax per capita, inflation adjusted).
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] California has the highest marginal income and capital gains tax rate and is in the top ten highest corporate tax and sales tax rates nationally.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 2016, California had the 17th-highest per-capita (per-person) property tax revenue in the country at $1,559, up from 31st in 1996.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 2019, WalletHub applied California's statewide effective property tax rate of 0.77% to the state median home market value of $443,400; the annual property taxes of $3,414 on the median home value was the 9th-highest in the United States.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 sets the assessed value of properties at the time of purchase (known as an acquisition value system), with a possible 2% annual assessment increase.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] As a result, properties of equal value can have a great amount of variation in their assessed value, even if they are next to each other.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The disparity grows when property prices appreciate by more than 2% a year.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The Case–Shiller housing index shows prices in Los Angeles, San Diego, and San Francisco appreciated 170% from 1987 (the start of available data) to 2012 while the 2% cap only allowed a 67% increase in taxes on homes that were not sold during this 26-year period.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It said that a revenue-neutral Los Angeles County reform which raises all assessments to true market value and lowers the property tax rate would harm elderly and low-income households.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] They also estimated that this effect was more pronounced in the coastal cities, with the increase in tenancy by owner-occupiers in the Bay Area being predicted at 28% (3.0 years), Los Angeles 21% (2.3 years), and Fresno 7% (0.77 years).
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] They speculate that renters may have longer tenure due to less turnover of owner-occupied housing to move into.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Other studies have found that increased tenure in renting can be attributed in part to rent control.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] A 2016 report from the California Legislative Analyst's Office found that property tax revenue to local governments was similarly volatile before and after the passage of Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] While Proposition 13 stabilized the base, prior to Proposition 13, governments would adjust the rate annually to counteract changes to the base.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] According to the California Building Industry Association, construction of a median priced house results in a slight positive fiscal impact, as opposed to the position that housing does not "pay its own way".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The trade association argues that this is because new homes are assessed at the value when they are first sold.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Additionally, due to the higher cost of new homes, the trade association claims that new residents are more affluent and may provide more sales tax revenues and use less social services of the host community.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Others argue that the real reason for the claimed negative effects is lack of trust for elected officials to spend the public's money wisely.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Business improvement districts are one means by which property owners have chosen to tax themselves for additional government services.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Property owners find that these targeted levies are more palatable than general taxes.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 alters the balance of the housing market because it provides disincentives for selling property, in favor of remaining at the current property and modifying or transferring to family members to avoid a new, higher property tax assessment.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 reduces property tax revenue for municipalities in California.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] They are forced to rely more on state funding and therefore may lose autonomy and control.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The amount of taxes available to the municipality in any given year largely depends on the number of property transfers taking place.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Yet since existing property owners have an incentive to remain in their property and not sell, there are fewer property transfers under this type of property tax system.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] California also has high rates of migrants from other countries and states, which has contributed to more demand for housing, and it has low amounts of moderately priced housing.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The different tax treatment can make real estate more valuable to the current owner than to any potential buyer, so selling it often makes no economic sense.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] These rules were subsequently changed; under current law, a change of control or ownership of a legal entity causes a reassessment of its real property as well as the real property of entities that it controls.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The application to commercial and rental property can lead to an advantage and profit margin for incumbent individuals or corporations who purchased property at a time when prices were low.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] This is in contrast to the initial campaign, where Jarvis argued that lowering property tax rates would cause landlords to pass savings onto renters, who were upset at their rapidly rising rents driven by the high inflation of the 1970s.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Most landlords did not do this, which became a motivating factor for rent control.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Some businesses have exploited a property transfer loophole in Proposition 13 implementing statutes created by the California Legislature that define what constitutes a change in property ownership.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] To take advantage of this loophole, businesses only have to make sure that no partnership exceeds the 50% mark in control in order to avoid a reassessment.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The Legislature could close this loophole with a 2/3 vote.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 2018, the California Board of Equalization estimated that closing this loophole would raise up to $269 million annually in new tax revenue.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] There have been several legislative attempts to close the loophole, none of which have been successful.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Local governments in California now use imaginative strategies to maintain or increase revenue due to Proposition 13 and the attendant loss of property tax revenue (which formerly went to cities, counties, and other local agencies).
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] For instance, many California local governments have sought voter approval for special taxes such as parcel taxes for public services that used to be paid for entirely or partially from property taxes imposed before Proposition 13 became law.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Provision for such taxes was made by the 1982 Community Facilities Act (more commonly known as Mello-Roos).
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Sales tax rates have also increased from 6% (pre-Proposition 13 level) to 7.25%, with cities such as Lancaster and Palmdale authorizing an 11.25% tax.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 1991, the Supreme Court of California ruled in *Rider v.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] County of San Diego* that a San Diego County sales tax to fund jail and courthouse construction was unconstitutional.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The court ruled that because the tax money was targeted towards specific programs rather than general spending, it counted as a "special tax" under Proposition 13 and required approval by two-thirds of the voters, whereas the tax had passed with a simple majority.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The imposition of these special taxes and fees was a target of California Proposition 218 ("Right to Vote on Taxes Act") which passed in 1996.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It constitutionally requires voter approval for local government taxes and some nontax levies such as benefit assessments on real property and certain property-related fees and charges.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 disproportionately affects coastal metropolitan areas, such as San Francisco and Los Angeles, where housing prices are higher, relative to inland communities with lower housing prices.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] According to the National Bureau of Economic Research, more research would show whether benefits of Proposition 13 outweigh the redistribution of tax base and overall cost in lost tax revenue.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Local governments have become more dependent on state funds, which has increased state power over local communities.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The state provides "block grants" to cities to provide services, and bought out some facilities that locally administer state-mandated programs.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Due to the reduction in revenue generated from property tax, local governments have become more dependent on sales taxes for general revenue funds.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Chapman, Michael Coleman and Betty Yee, maintain that this trend resulted in the "fiscalization of land use", meaning that land use decisions are influenced by the ability of a new development to generate revenue.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] This may discourage growth of other sectors and job types that may provide better opportunities for residents.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In terms of public services, office and retail development are further incentivized because they do not cost the local governments as much as residential developments.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Additionally, cities have decreased services and increased fees to compensate for the shortfall, with particularly high impact fees levied on developers to impose the cost of the additional services and infrastructure that new developments will require.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] These costs are typically shifted to the building's buyer, who may be unaware of the thousands in fees included with the building's cost.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] California's K-12 public schools, which during the 1960s had been ranked nationally as among the best, deteriorated substantially in many surveys of student achievement, according to a 2005 RAND study.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Priest*, and Proposition 13 was then passed partially as a result of that case.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] California's spending per pupil was the same as the national average until about 1985, when it began decreasing, which resulted in another referendum, Proposition 98, that requires a certain percentage of the state's budget to be directed towards public education.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] One measure of K-12 public school spending is the percentage of personal income that a state spends on education.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] From a peak of about 4.5% for the nation overall, and 4.0% for California, both peaking in the early 1970s, the nation overall as well as California spent declining percentages on public education in the decade from 1975 to 1985.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] For the longer period of 1970–2008, California had always spent a lower percentage than the rest of the nation on education.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] UCSD Economics Professor Julian Betts stated in a 2010 interview: "What all this means for spending is that starting around 1978–1979 we saw a sharp reduction in spending on schools.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Bureau of Economic Analysis and by the Public Policy Institute of California.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] This resulted in increased pupil-to-teacher ratios in K-12 public schools in California.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] These measures significantly closed the K-12 spending gap between California and the national average.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Pupil-teacher ratios decreased since the passage of Proposition 30, and according to a National Education Association survey, California had the second-highest starting teacher salary among the 50 states in 2018.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 is consistently popular among California's likely voters, 64% of whom were homeowners as of 2017.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] A 2018 survey from the Public Policy Institute of California found that 57% of Californians say that Proposition 13 is mostly a good thing, while 23% say it is mostly a bad thing.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] 65% of likely voters say it has been mostly a good thing, as do: 71% of Republicans, 55% of Democrats, and 61% of independents; 54% of people age 18 to 34, 52% of people age 35 to 54, and 66% of people 55 and older; 65% of homeowners and 50% of renters.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The only demographic group for which less than 50% said that Proposition 13 was mostly a good thing was African Americans, at 39%.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] At the same time, a majority of both Californians (55%) and likely voters (56%) opposed lowering the supermajority threshold for local special taxes.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 13 is often considered the "third rail" of California politics, which means that politicians avoid discussions of changing it.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In the 2003 California recall election in which Arnold Schwarzenegger was elected governor, his advisor Warren Buffett suggested that Proposition 13 be repealed or changed as a method of balancing the state's budget.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Gavin Newsom, when asked about the fairness of Proposition 13 in a 2010 interview with *The Bay Citizen*, said: "The political realities are such that Democrats, not just Republicans and Independents, are overwhelmingly opposed to making adjustments in terms of the residential side of Prop.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 2011, California Governor Jerry Brown was quoted as saying that it wasn't Proposition 13 that was the problem, but "It was what the Legislature did after 13, it was what happened after 13 was passed" because the legislature reduced local authorities' power.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In a later interview in 2014, he lamented that he hadn't built up a "war chest" with which to campaign for an alternative to Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Governor Brown said he'd learned from his failure in the mid-1970s to build a war chest that he could have used to push an alternative to Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Governor Brown was definitive that he would not seek to change the law, a third rail in California politics.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] 13 is a sacred doctrine that should never be questioned," he said.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 8 allows for a reassessment of real property values in a declining market.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 58 allowed homeowners to transfer their principal residence to children without a property tax re-assessment, as well as the first $1 million (not indexed to inflation) in assessed value of other real property.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] They estimated total foregone yearly property tax revenue for all exemptions ever received at $1.5 billion in 2015, or about 2.5% of total statewide property tax revenue.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The report said that while the exemption made it possible for some to live in their parents' house, it likely incentivized the conversion of inherited houses into rental property or other uses.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The report said the exemption probably created downward pressure on rents while causing more Californians to be renters rather than homeowners.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 60 allows homeowners over the age of 55 to transfer the assessed value of their present home to a replacement home if the replacement home is located in the same county, is of equal or lesser value, and purchased within two years of sale.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 90 was similar to 1986 Proposition 60 in that it allowed homeowners over the age of 55 to transfer the assessed value of their present home to a replacement home if the replacement home was located in a different county, provided the incoming county allowed the transfer.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 193 extended 1986 Proposition 58 by allowing grandparents to transfer to their grandchildren their primary residence and up to $1 million (not indexed to inflation) in other real property without a property tax re-assessment, when both parents of the grandchild are deceased.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 218, called the "Right to Vote on Taxes Act," is an initiative constitutional amendment approved by California voters on November 5, 1996.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 218 was sponsored by the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association as a constitutional follow-up to Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The proposition established constitutional limits on the ability of local governments to levy benefit assessments on real property and property-related fees and charges such as those for utility services to property.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The assessment and property-related fee and charge reforms contained in Proposition 218 were in response to California local governments' use of revenue sources that circumvented the two-thirds vote requirement to raise local taxes under Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It also requires voter approval before a local government, including a charter city, may impose, increase, or extend any local tax.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It also constitutionally reserves to local voters the right to use the initiative power to reduce or repeal any local tax, assessment, fee or charge, including provision for a significantly reduced petition signature requirement to qualify a measure on the ballot.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 39 lowered the required supermajority necessary for voters to impose local school bond acts from two-thirds (2/3) of the votes cast to 55%.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 26 added a constitutional definition of "tax" for purposes of the two-thirds legislative vote requirement for state taxes under Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Following the defeat of Proposition 5 in 2018, the California Association of Realtors sponsored another measure similar to their prior initiative.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It appeared on the November 2020 ballot and was approved by voters by a narrow margin.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Since its passage in 1978, there have been many attempts to change Proposition 13 through legislation, legal challenges, and additional ballot measures.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 1992, a legal challenge (*Nordlinger v.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Hahn*) was considered by the United States Supreme Court, which subsequently ruled 8–1 that Proposition 13 didn't violate the Equal Protection clause, and found Nordlinger didn't have standing to raise a Right to Travel claim.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Stephanie Nordlinger had purchased a property in the Los Angeles area in 1988 and, under the provisions of Proposition 13, was required to have the property reassessed at a new value.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The reassessed value of Nordlinger's property raised her tax rates by 36%, while her neighbors continued to pay significantly lower rates on their property.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Disheartened by the disparity in taxation, Nordlinger viewed this reassessment as favoritism in the eyes of the law and elected to bring charges up on the Los Angeles County Tax Assessment office and its primary assessor, Kenneth Hahn.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Nordlinger subsequently sued the Los Angeles County Tax Assessor Kenneth Hahn on the grounds of the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The Supreme Court held in *Nordlinger v.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Hahn* that Proposition 13 was constitutional.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Justice Harry Blackmun, writing the majority opinion, noted that California had a "legitimate interest in local neighborhood preservation, continuity, and stability" and that it was acceptable to treat owners who have invested for some time in property differently from new owners.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] One who objected to the rules could choose not to buy.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Nordlinger also raised a right to travel argument—however, justices found that she lacked standing, as she wasn't impeded from moving to California by Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Thirty years after purchasing her house, Nordlinger, now a senior citizen on a limited income, paid $3,400 a year in property taxes on the house, which had increased in value to $900,000.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Young, former University of California, Los Angeles chancellor, brought a lawsuit with a team of lawyers headed by William Norris, a retired federal judge of the United States 9th Circuit Court of Appeals.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] They unsuccessfully sued to overturn the Proposition 13 requirement that a two-thirds (2/3) vote of the Legislature is required to increase state taxes.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The property transfer loophole was almost closed in 2014 by a bipartisan coalition in the state legislature but the effort died after progressive politicians, organized labor, and community groups refused to support the effort.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] In 2015 and 2018, Republican efforts to fix this loophole were stalled by Democratic state legislators in legislative committee.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Another Republican attempt to close the loophole was made in 2020.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Democrat Don Perata, former California senate leader, said this loophole is left open by his party to create justification for ending Proposition 13.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proposition 5 would have extended 1986 California Proposition 60 and 1988 California Proposition 90 by providing property tax savings to all homeowners who are over age 55 (or who meet other qualifications) when they move to a different home.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It was sponsored by the California Association of Realtors.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] California's Legislative Analyst's Office estimated that this would cost local governments about $100 million per year over the first few years, growing to $1 billion per year (in 2018 dollars) over time.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] It was defeated on November 6, 2018, with approximately 58% of voters not in favor.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The measure failed to pass, with 52% of votes cast in opposition to the measure.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] Proponents of the measure were outspent by the opposition, with supporters having spent $69 million while opponents spent $74 million.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] 15 were the California Teachers Association, multiple chapters of the Service Employees International Union, and the Chan Zuckerberg Advocacy Fund.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/1978-california-proposition-13] The main opposition donors were corporate and business oriented groups including the California Business Roundtable, Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association, the Business Property Association, and the real estate industry.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] Proposition 20 was decisively rejected by 62% of Californians, a margin of 24 percentage points.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] Observers partly attributed its failure to the George Floyd protests bringing negative attention to punitive criminal justice policies.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] This measure was being supported by law enforcement unions, grocery store chains, and current California State Assembly member and former law enforcement officer Jim Cooper.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] The measure was opposed by the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, former governor Jerry Brown, and the American Civil Liberties Union.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] The *Los Angeles Times* announced its opposition to the Proposition in October 2020.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] Opponents cited the impact that the COVID-19 pandemic has had on crowded prisons, and argue that prisons should not hold any more people than they already do.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] In addition, they also cite the disparate impact that America's criminal justice system has on African Americans, a concern that has increased in the wake of the murder of George Floyd.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] According to opponents Proposition 20 would have increased the prison population, thereby increasing state and local court, correctional, and law enforcement costs by tens of millions of dollars annually.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] Had it passed, it would have partially reversed the results of Proposition 47, Proposition 57, and other legislation that have been intended to reduce the prison population and shift the correctional system from a punitive system to a rehabilitative system.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-california-proposition-20] In order to pass, it needs a simple majority (>50%).
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] The **2020 Facebook ad boycotts** were a group of boycotts that took place during the month of July 2020.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] Much of the boycotts were organized under the **Stop Hate for Profit** campaign, launched by the advocacy groups the Anti-Defamation League, the NAACP, Color of Change, Common Sense Media, Free Press and Sleeping Giants.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] Over 1,000 companies participated in the boycott.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] In June 2020, Facebook refused to censor a post that contained Donald Trump's "When the looting starts, the shooting starts" statement, as well as a post by Trump that criticized the CHAZ.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] Mark Zuckerberg later defended this move.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] This led to immense criticism and later became one of the factors leading to the boycott.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] According to Jonathan Greenblatt, one of the organizers behind the boycott, the idea for the boycott arose because his organization thought that Facebook was not doing enough to censor hate speech.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] He requested a meeting with Facebook representatives but was turned down.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] After communicating with Rashad Robinson and Derrick Johnson, the three of them launched the campaign.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] On June 17, the Anti-Defamation League, the NAACP, Color of Change, Common Sense Media, Free Press and Sleeping Giants revealed the Stop Hate for Profit campaign through a full-page ad in the Los Angeles Times.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] The coalition of organizations grew to include the League of United Latin American Citizens, Mozilla and the National Hispanic Media Coalition.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] The Stop Hate for Profit campaign called for an ad pause in June 2020, asking companies to pause spending on Facebook and Instagram ads for July 2020.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] On June 19, The North Face and REI announced their plans to join the boycott.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] Shortly thereafter, Upwork and Patagonia announced that they would join the boycott.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] On June 24, Ben & Jerry's announced that it would join the boycott.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] The next day, Verizon announced that it would join the boycott.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] On June 26, Unilever announced that it would join the boycott.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] The next day, one of the organizers of the boycott announced that the boycott would now aim to include European companies.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] In addition, Coca-Cola announced that it would join the boycott.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] On July 7, the organizers of the boycott met with Facebook representatives as well as Zuckerberg.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] The organizers disliked the meeting, and brought up how Facebook did not set any dates or make detailed plans.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] Writing for *The Verge*, Casey Newton argued that the companies that took part in the boycott acted "as if Facebook doesn't ban hate speech at all", and that the boycott should've focused on the company's monopoly power.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] Several writers noted that many businesses had already cut their marketing budgets due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] Most of Facebook's revenue comes from small to mid-sized companies, and the top 100 advertisers only comprise 6% of the total revenue, suggesting that a boycott would be futile.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] The long-term impact of the boycott was expected to be minimal, as an industry analyst predicted that advertisers would ramp up spending during the period.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] On June 26, the share price of Facebook dropped by 8.3%.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] On the same day, Mark Zuckerberg stated that the company would begin to place "warning labels" on posts such as those by Trump.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] In addition, the company would prohibit certain types of ads and misinformation related to voting.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] This was criticized by the organizers of the boycott.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] On June 30, Facebook removed several groups and users associated with the Boogaloo movement.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2020-facebook-ad-boycotts] In August 2020, Facebook and Instagram began removing 1,500 QAnon pages and groups that discussed violence, and in early October reportedly committed to removing all QAnon content, even if it does not explicitly refer to violence.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In 2021, an internal document leak from Facebook (now Meta Platforms, or Meta) showed it was aware of harmful societal effects from its platforms, yet persisted in prioritizing profit over addressing these harms.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The leak, released by whistleblower Frances Haugen, resulted in reporting from *The Wall Street Journal* in September, as ***The Facebook Files*** series from journalist Jeff Horwitz, as well as the ***Facebook Papers***, by a consortium of news outlets the next months.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Primarily, the reports revealed that, based on internally commissioned studies, the company was fully aware of negative impacts on teenage users of Instagram, and the contribution of Facebook activity to violence in developing countries.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Other takeaways of the leak include the impact of the company's platforms on spreading false information, and Facebook's policy of promoting inflammatory posts.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Furthermore, Facebook was fully aware that harmful content was being pushed through Facebook algorithms reaching young users.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The types of content included posts promoting anorexia nervosa and self-harm photos.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In October 2021, Whistleblower Aid filed eight anonymous whistleblower complaints with the U.S.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) on behalf of Haugen alleging securities fraud by the company, after Haugen leaked the company documents the previous month.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] After publicly revealing her identity on *60 Minutes*, Haugen testified before the U.S.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Senate Commerce Subcommittee on Consumer Protection, Product Safety, and Data Security about the content of the leaked documents and the complaints.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] After the company renamed itself as **Meta Platforms**, Whistleblower Aid filed two additional securities fraud complaints with the SEC against the company on behalf of Haugen in February 2022.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In response to the media fallout, Facebook executives went on press tours to express Facebook's position amidst the frenzy.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Facebook also did internal damage control with employees through in person sessions and memos.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In mid September 2021, *The Wall Street Journal* began publishing articles on Facebook based on internal documents from unknown provenance.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The leaked documents include internal research from Facebook that studied the impact of Instagram on teenage mental health.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Although Facebook claimed earlier that its rules applies equally to everyone on the platform, internal documents shared with *The Wall Street Journal* point to special policy exceptions reserved for VIP users, including celebrities and politicians.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] After this reporting, Facebook's oversight board said it would review the system.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] On October 3, 2021, the former Facebook employee behind the leak, Frances Haugen, revealed her identity on a *60 Minutes* interview where she detailed the harm Facebook knowingly allowed on their platform.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In her interview, she explains that her friend falling subject to propaganda is what pushed her to be so vocal about the misdoings of Facebook.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Beginning October 22, a group of news outlets began publishing articles based on documents provided by Haugen's lawyers, collectively referred to as *The Facebook Papers*.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] These articles detailed the various crimes Facebook was complicit in.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Another of the whistleblower complaints Haugen filed with the SEC alleged that the company misled investors and the general public about enforcement of its terms of service due to such whitelisting under the XCheck program.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The Files show that Facebook (now Meta) had been conducting internal research of how Instagram affects young users since 2018.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] While the findings point to Instagram being harmful to a large portion of young users, teenage girls were among the most harmed.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Researchers within the company reported that "we make body issues worse for one in three teenage girls".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Furthermore, internal research revealed that teen boys were also affected by negative social comparison, citing 14% of boys in the U.S. in 2019.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Instagram was concluded to contribute to problems more specific to its app use, such as social comparison among teens.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Facebook published some of its internal research on September 29, 2021, saying these reports mischaracterized the purpose and results of its research.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The Files show that Facebook formed a team to study preteens, set a three-year goal to create more products for this demographic, and commissioned strategy papers about the long-term business prospects of attracting the preteen demographic.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Some research Facebook has done includes studies on tween usage of social media apps and parent responses.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Federal privacy laws, including the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act (COPPA), restrict data collection on children under 13 years old.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Internal documents from April 2021 showed plans to make apps targeting children from ages six to 17, by September, the head of Instagram announced the halting of development of those apps.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] An internal memo seen by *The Washington Post* revealed that Facebook has been aware of hate speech and calls for violence against groups like Muslims and Kashmiris in 2019, including posts of photos of piles of dead Kashmiri bodies with glorifying captions on its platform in India.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Still, none of their publishers were blocked.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Documents reveal Facebook has responded to these incidents by removing posts which violate their policy, but has not made any substantial efforts to prevent repeat offenses.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] As 90% of monthly Facebook users are now located outside of the U.S. and Canada, Facebook claimed language barriers were one obstacle that is preventing widespread reform (around 2019-2021).
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In 2015, in addition to the Like button on posts, Facebook introduced a set of other emotional reaction options: love, haha, yay, wow, sad and angry.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] *The Washington Post* reported that for three years, Facebook's algorithms promoted posts receiving the new reactions (including the 'angry' reaction) from its users; giving them a score five times that of traditional likes.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Years later, Facebook's researchers pointed out that posts with 'angry' reactions were much more likely to be toxic, polarizing, fake or low quality.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Ignoring frequent internal calls, the company did not differentiate the 'angry' reaction from other reactions until September 2019, when its value was cut to zero (only after realizing users' dissatisfaction over their posts receiving angry reactions).
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] There have been other cases when Facebook prioritized new features it wanted to promote, despite this turning out to be promoting toxic or radicalizing material.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In 2018, Facebook overhauled its News Feed algorithm, implementing a new algorithm which favored "Meaningful Social Interactions" or "MSI".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The new algorithm increased the weight of reshared material—a move which aimed to "reverse the decline in comments and encourage more original posting".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] While the algorithm was successful in its efforts, consequences such as user reports of feed quality decreasing along with increased anger on the site were observed.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Leaked documents reveal that employees presented several potential changes to fix some of the highlighted issues with their algorithm.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] However, documents claim Mark Zuckerberg denied the proposed changes due to his worry that they might cause fewer users to engage with Facebook.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Documents have also pointed to another 2019 study conducted by Facebook where a fake account based in India was created and studied to see what type of content it was presented and interacted with.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Results of the study showed that within three weeks, the fake account's newsfeed was being presented pornography and "filled with polarizing and graphic content, hate speech and misinformation", according to an internal company report.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In 2019, following concerns about Facebook and Instagram being used to trade maids in the Middle East, Apple threatened to remove their iOS apps from the App Store.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Facebook, then, promised to enforce stronger regulations, yet later stated that it was under-enforcing them.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Two years later, a search on Facebook for maids would still yield results of workers.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] These maids have reported being starved, sold, locked in their homes, and physically assaulted.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The documents have shown a private program known as "XCheck" or "cross-check" that Facebook has employed in order to whitelist posts from users deemed as "high-profile".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The system began as a quality control measure but has since grown to protect "millions of VIP users from the company's normal enforcement process".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] XCheck has led to celebrities and other public figures being exempt from punishment that the average Facebook user would receive from violating policies.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In 2019, football player Neymar had posted nude photos of a woman who had accused him of rape which were left up for more than a day.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, "XCheck grew to include at least 5.8 million users in 2020" according to Facebook's internal documents.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The goal of XCheck was "to never publicly tangle with anyone who is influential enough to do you harm".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In 2020, Vietnam's communist government threatened to shut down Facebook if the social media company did not cooperate on censoring political content in the country, Facebook's (now Meta's) biggest market in Southeast Asia.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The decision to comply was personally approved by Mark Zuckerberg.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] By the end of 2020, it was reported by Facebook that they had increased censorship by 983% in comparison to the last report.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In 2021, Facebook developed a new strategy for addressing harmful content on their site, implementing measures which were designed to reduce and suppress the spread of movements that were deemed hateful.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] According to a senior security official at Facebook, the company "would seek to disrupt on-platform movements only if there was compelling evidence that they were the product of tightly knit circles of users connected to real-world violence or other harm and committed to violating Facebook's rules".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] As part of their recently coordinated initiative, this included less promotion of the movement's posts within users' News Feed as well as not notifying users of new posts from these pages.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, documents show that in 2019, Facebook reduced the time spent by human reviewers on hate-speech complaints, shifting towards a stronger dependence on their artificial intelligence systems to regulate the matter.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] However, internal documents from employees claim that their AI has been largely unsuccessful, seeing trouble detecting videos of cars crashing, cockfighting, as well as understanding hate speech in foreign languages.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Internal engineers and researchers within Facebook have estimated that their AI has only been able to detect and remove 0.6% of "all content that violated Facebook's policies against violence and incitement".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In the Q3 2021 earnings call, Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg discussed the recent leaks, characterizing them as coordinated efforts to paint a false picture of his company by selectively leaking documents.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] According to a leaked internal email seen by *The New York Times*, Facebook asked its employees to "preserve internal documents and communications since 2016", a practice called a legal hold.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In December 2021, news broke on *The Wall Street Journal* pointing to Meta's lobbying efforts to divide U.S. lawmakers and "muddy the waters" in Congress, to hinder regulation following the 2021 whistleblower leaks.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] According to the article, the company's goal was to "muddy the waters, divide lawmakers along partisan lines and forestall a cross-party alliance" against Facebook (now Meta) in Congress.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In October 2021, Nick Clegg went on a press tour to communicate Facebook's position in the wake of Haugen testifying and exposing Facebook's harmful practices.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Nick Clegg was a Facebook executive up until 2025 and also served as the British deputy prime minister.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Facebook sent company executives on a few press tours to fix some of the damage caused by the media and the public's reaction to the Facebook Papers.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Facebook also held a few internal press tours for damage control amongst employees and to gauge their reactions.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] This involved vice presidents holding meetings with employees on specific topics, such as polarization and the company's feelings towards it, as well as how executives were keeping the platform safe.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Facebook also sent out memos as guidelines for how employees should be publicly reacting to this event.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The memos they sent out also included a statement about how Facebook does not prioritize profit over safety.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Facebook employees felt split in the wake of Haugen's testimony.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] With the unprecedented resources we have, we should do better." It was clear to many employees that this event was long coming.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] In the wake of the fallout of Haugen's testimony, Facebook decided to make some changes.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The first and biggest public move was changing their name from Facebook to Meta.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] They also unveiled a new logo, moving away from the iconic blue Facebook logo to an infinity symbol.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] This was announced in a video by Mark Zuckerberg.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] He went on to explain Metas' commitment to the future and a few projects they are working on.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Facebook also went on to halt production on its Instagram For Kids feature after backlash surrounding its platform's impact on children.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Adam Mosseri, the head of Instagram, put out a statement explaining that this feature is still something they are committed to expanding, but in the moment, they want to consult with more experts before taking the project to beta testing.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Mosseri maintained that there needs to be a platform available for children.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] While Facebook continues to figure out how to resume work on Instagram For Kids, they announced they will expand parental supervision.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] The book *Broken Code: Inside Facebook and the Fight to Expose Its Harmful Secrets* was published in November 2023 by *The Wall Street Journal* technology reporter Jeff Horwitz.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] Horwitz's book is the base of an upcoming feature film *The Social Reckoning*, written and directed by Aaron Sorkin.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-leak] With Jeremy Strong starring as Zuckerberg, Mikey Madison as Haugen, and Jeremy Allen White as Horwitz, the film is slated to be released on October 9, 2026.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] On October 4, 2021, at 15:39 UTC, the social network Facebook and its subsidiaries, Messenger, Instagram, WhatsApp, Mapillary, and Oculus, became globally unavailable for a period of six to seven hours.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] The outage also prevented anyone trying to use "Log in with Facebook" from accessing third-party sites.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] During the outage, many users flocked to Twitter, Discord, Signal, and Telegram, resulting in disruptions on these sites' servers.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] The outage was caused by the loss of IP routes to the Facebook Domain Name System (DNS) servers, which were all self-hosted at the time.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] Security experts identified the problem as a Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) withdrawal of the IP address prefixes in which Facebook's Domain Name System (DNS) servers were hosted, making it impossible for users to resolve Facebook and related domain names, and reach services.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] Effects were visible globally; for example, Swiss Internet service provider Init7 recorded a massive drop in internet traffic to the Facebook servers after the change in the Border Gateway Protocol.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] Cloudflare reported that at 15:39 UTC, Facebook made a significant number of BGP updates, including the withdrawal of routes to the IP prefixes, which included all of their authoritative nameservers.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] This made Facebook's DNS servers unreachable from the Internet.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] By 15:50 UTC, Facebook's domains had expired from the caches in all major public resolvers.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] A little before 21:00 UTC, Facebook resumed announcing BGP updates, with Facebook's domain name becoming resolvable again at 21:05 UTC.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] On October 5, Facebook's engineering team posted a blog post explaining the cause of the outage.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] During maintenance, a command was run to assess the global backbone capacity, and that command accidentally disconnected all of Facebook's data centers.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] While Facebook's DNS servers ran on a separate network, they were designed to withdraw their BGP routes if they could not connect to Facebook's data centers, making it impossible for the rest of the internet to connect to Facebook.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] Facebook gradually returned after a team got access to server computers at the Santa Clara, California, data center and reset them.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] By about 22:45 UTC, Facebook and related services were generally available again.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] The outage cut off Facebook's internal communications, preventing employees from sending or receiving external emails, accessing the corporate directory, and authenticating to some Google Docs and Zoom services.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] *The New York Times* reported that employees were unable to access buildings and conference rooms with their security badges.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] The site Downdetector, which monitors network outages, recorded over 10 million problem reports – the largest number for an incident to date.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] The Google Public DNS service also slowed down as a result of the outage, while users of Gmail, TikTok, and Snapchat also experienced slowdowns.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] CNBC reported that the outage was the worst experienced by Facebook since 2008.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] During the day of the outage, shares in the company dropped by nearly 5% and Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg's wealth fell by more than $6 billion.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] According to a report produced by *Fortune* and Snopes, Facebook lost at least $60 million in advertising revenue.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] The outage had a major impact on people in the developing world, who depend on Facebook's "Free Basics" program, affecting communication, business and humanitarian work.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, a U.S. representative from New York, tweeted about the outage, asking people to share "evidence-based" stories on Twitter, making fun of Facebook's reputation for spreading factually questionable content.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] Twitter and Reddit also posted tweets on their official Twitter accounts commenting on the outage.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] Users on both Twitter and Telegram reported a slowdown in response times, believed to be caused by people normally on Facebook services switching to those services.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/2021-facebook-outage] Some media outlets highlighted the coincidence of Frances Haugen's testimony with that of the outage, although those two events are unrelated to each other.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] An **activity stream** is a list of recent activities performed by an individual, typically on a single website.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] For example, Facebook's News Feed is an activity stream.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] Since the introduction of the News Feed on September 6, 2006, other major websites have introduced similar implementations for their own users.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] Since the proliferation of activity streams on websites, there have been calls to standardize the format so that websites could interact with a stream provided by another website.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] The Activity Streams project, for example, is an effort to develop an activity stream protocol to syndicate activities across social web applications.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] Several major websites with activity stream implementations have already opened up their activity streams to developers to use, including Facebook and MySpace.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] Though activity stream arises from social networking, nowadays it has become an essential part of business software.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] Enterprise social software is used in different types of companies to organize their internal communication and acts as an addition to traditional corporate intranet.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] Collaboration software like Jive Software, Yammer, and Chatter offer activity stream as a separate product.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/activity-stream] At the same time other software providers such as tibbr, Central Desktop, and Wrike offer activity stream as an integrated part of their collaboration software solution.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] Adam D'Angelo was born on August 14, 1984, in Redding, Connecticut, United States.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] He attended Phillips Exeter Academy for high school.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] While a student there, he developed the Synapse Media Player (a music suggestion program) with Exeter classmate Mark Zuckerberg and others.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] From 2002 to 2006, D'Angelo attended the California Institute of Technology, where he graduated with a B.S. in computer science.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] In 2004, while attending college, D'Angelo created the website BuddyZoo, which allowed users to upload their AIM buddy list in order to compare with those of other users.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] BuddyZoo also generated network graphs based on these lists.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] D'Angelo joined Facebook shortly after its launch in 2004, and was its chief technology officer (CTO) from 2006 to 2008, and vice president of engineering until 2008.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] In June 2009, D'Angelo co-founded Quora with former Facebook software engineer, Charlie Cheever.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] In May 2012, he invested $20 million in Quora as part of the company's $50 million Series B round of financing.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] D'Angelo was also an early investor in Instagram before its 2012 acquisition by Facebook, Asana, a work management platform, and Lunchclub, a networking platform using artificial intelligence.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] D'Angelo is the founder of an AI startup, Poe.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] Poe is currently integrated within Quora.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] D'Angelo was an early advisor to Instagram prior to 2012.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] In 2018, he joined the board of directors of OpenAI.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] In November 2023, D'Angelo was one of four board members who voted to remove Sam Altman from his role as CEO of OpenAI.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] When Altman returned to OpenAI, the other three board members involved in Altman's ouster resigned.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/adam-d-angelo] D'Angelo was the only of the six original board members who remained following Altman's return.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The **Chan Zuckerberg Initiative** (**CZI**) is an organization established and owned by Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg and his wife Priscilla Chan with an investment of 99 percent of the couple's wealth from their Facebook shares over their lifetime.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The CZI is legally set up as a limited liability company (LLC) that can be seen as a for-profit charity and is an example of philanthrocapitalism.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] CZI has been deemed likely to be "one of the most well-funded philanthropies in human history".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Chan and Zuckerberg announced its creation on 1 December 2015, to coincide with the birth of their first child.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Chan has said that her background as a child of immigrant refugees and experience as a teacher and pediatrician for vulnerable children influences how she approaches the philanthropy's work in science, education, immigration reform, housing, criminal justice, and other local issues.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative's main areas of work include science, education, and justice and opportunity, which focuses on promoting housing affordability, criminal justice reform, and immigration reform.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The mission of the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative is to "build a more inclusive, just, and healthy future for everyone" and to "advance human potential and promote equality in areas such as health, education, scientific research and energy".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In 2017, the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative pre-leased a 102,079 square foot portion of the new Broadway Station development in downtown Redwood City, California, where it is headquartered.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] After the election of Donald Trump as US president and the discontinuation of government and Meta Diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) programs, CZI initially announced on 10 January 2025 that it would continue its diversity programs.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Critiques have been made regarding CZI, as it often tries to solve problems caused by social media, including Zuckerberg's very own social media platforms.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative invested $24 million in Andela, a startup focused on training software developers in Africa through a boot camp and four-year fellowship program that pairs their trainees with U.S. companies needing development help.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative led the company's Series B funding.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In 2016, Chan and CZI co-founded The Primary School, a non-profit organization that promised to provide K–12 education, prenatal care, early childhood education, primary health care, and other programs and services for free to residents in East Palo Alto, California and the surrounding areas.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] She served as the emeritus board chair of the school.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In 2022, The Primary School received approximately $8 million in donations, and in 2023, the school recorded nearly $4 million in contributions.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In April 2025, CZI announced that the school would close at the end of the 2025-2026 school year.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] CZI pledged $50 million over five years to "parent engagement programs, early childhood education and health care services" in "the East Palo Alto, Belle Haven, and East Bay communities".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] As of April 2026, when a notice of staff layoffs was submitted to the state department of employment, the school had approximately 550 students on two campuses, in East Palo Alto and San Leandro.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In September 2016, Indian education startup Byju's announced raising $50 million in a round co-led by The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative and Sequoia Capital, along with investors Sofina, Lightspeed Venture Partners, and Times Internet.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The funding has been raised to fuel their international expansion.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] On 6 March 2018, the Harvard Gazette published that the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative would pledge $30 million to the Reach Every Reader project.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Both Harvard's President Drew Faust and MIT's President L.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Rafael Reif were quoted in the article, as were Priscilla Chan, HGSE Dean James E.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Ryan, and MIT's Sanjay Sarma, VP for Open Learning at MIT, and others.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The article states: "To make significant progress in early literacy at scale, the team will engage in a rigorous, scientific approach to personalized diagnosis and intervention.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In 2018, CZI announced it was supporting the development of a civic tech talent pipeline by funding Coding it Forward.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] No discrete information was provided about the quality or quantity of funding.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Initiative has funded a free online learning platform, Summit Learning, that is based on a personalized learning philosophy.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The use of the platform in some schools has led to concerns about efficacy and student privacy.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In May 2022, the Chan Zuckerberg initiative announced grants totaling more than $4 million in support of education communities.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The grants will support a range of professional learning, mentoring, and wellness practices to support teacher retention.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The grants include $1 million donations to FuelED, The Teacher Well, Profound Gentlemen, and $500,000 to Profound Ladies and Black Male Educators Alliance of Michigan.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, in partnership with The San Francisco Foundation and other philanthropic, business, and health organizations, created the Partnership for the Bay's Future in 2019 to "preserve, produce, and protect affordable housing".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Partnership includes a $500+ million fund for subsidized affordable housing units in the Bay Area, as well as grants for local governments and community organizations to work together to pass local housing legislation that protects tenants and promotes affordability.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] On 1 October 2018, The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative announced it was helping to launch Opportunity Insights, a new non-partisan, not-for-profit research and policy institute focused on improving economic opportunity led by Raj Chetty, John Friedman, and Nathaniel Hendren.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The research aims to "better understand the drivers of poverty as well as solutions that can foster greater economic mobility and security for more families".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative supported the failed campaign for the 2020 California Proposition 15, which would have adjusted the original 1978 California Proposition 13 by raising large commercial property taxes.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In addition, the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative opposed the failed 2020 California Proposition 20, a measure which would have led to stricter sentencing and parole laws.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Following electoral defeats of CZI-backed initiatives in 2020, the CZI announced a restructuring that would no longer fund political campaigns directly.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In September 2016, CZI announced its new science program, Chan Zuckerberg Science, with $3 billion in investment over the next decade, with Cornelia Bargmann of Rockefeller University announced as the first president of science, to begin 1 October 2016.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Commentators saw the move as an audacious but worthwhile goal, while noting that the amount of funding is small relative to overall money spent on biomedical research.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] This funding is equal to roughly 2% of the NIH budget earmarked for basic research over the same time frame.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Any patents generated at Biohub would be jointly owned by Biohub and the discoverer's home institution.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative's first acquisition took place in January 2017 with the acquisition of Meta, a Toronto-based artificial intelligence scientific literature search engine that helps scientists collaborate on solutions and accelerates the dissemination of new scientific research.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] On 28 October 2021, CZI announced the sunset of Meta, with a proposed shutdown date of 31 March 2022.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative was a founding sponsor of the Vector Institute for Artificial Intelligence at Toronto's MaRS Discovery District in March 2017.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative invested heavily in coronavirus research and response following the COVID-19 outbreak in 2020.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The organization has contributed multiple grants to various universities and partnerships studying how the coronavirus spreads and possible treatments or vaccines.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Biohub partnered with Stanford and UCSF to help to significantly increase free testing in the Bay Area starting in March 2020.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In April 2020, CZI joined the Government of the United Kingdom and Madonna in pledging funding for the COVID-19 Therapeutics Accelerator, a public-private partnership led by the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, Wellcome Trust and Mastercard.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Biohub announced in July 2020 that it would partner with all 58 California county departments of public health to provide free genomic sequencing of positive coronavirus samples to better understand how the virus is spreading and inform policy decisions.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative has also invested in the development and maintenance of open-source scientific software, with a pledge of US$40 million over 3 years for its Essential Open Source Software for Science (EOSS) program.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] CZI's Open Science program also supports the preprint servers medRxiv and BioRxiv." Grants included support to projects such as ScientificPython and the visualization library matplotlib.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Besides directly funding projects, CZI's Open Science division organizes workshops with grantees and stakeholders outside the United States to foster "global participation in open biomedical research".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] After the election of Donald Trump as US president and the discontinuation of government diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) programs, CZI announced on 10 January 2025 that it would continue its diversity programs.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] In 2025 CZI informed programs which could be associated with DEI, including many of their San Mateo County partners, that their funding would not be continued and that they would not be eligible for funding going forward.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] This was sharply criticized by a number of CZI employees as well as the impacted charities.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative is not a charitable trust or a private foundation but a limited liability company, and is therefore not a tax-exempt organization as many philanthropies are.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] Under this legal structure, *Forbes* wrote, "Zuckerberg will still control the Facebook shares owned by the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative".
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative publicly lists its grants, a level of transparency not required for an LLC.
[src:chan-zuckerberg-initiative/chan-zuckerberg-initiative] It pledged in 2020 to release software developed by it or its grantees under open-source licenses.
